    description: `Taqwiyat-ul-Iman (Strengthening of Faith) is a foundational Islamic text authored by the eminent scholar and martyr Shah Ismail Shaheed (rahimahullah), one of the most influential figures in the history of Islamic revival in the Indian subcontinent. Originally written in Urdu during the early 19th century, this English translation brings the timeless message of pure Tawheed to a global readership seeking to understand and fortify their Islamic creed. The book was composed during a period when polytheistic practices, cultural superstitions, and syncretic rituals had deeply permeated Muslim society, particularly in the regions of India. Shah Ismail Shaheed, a grandson of Shah Waliullah Dehlawi and a close companion of Sayyid Ahmad Shaheed, recognized that the deterioration of Muslim faith was directly linked to the erosion of correct Aqeedah. Taqwiyat-ul-Iman was his response to this crisis, written in plain and accessible language so that common Muslims could understand the core tenets of their religion without requiring advanced scholarly training.

The book systematically addresses the concept of Tawheed (the oneness of Allah) and dismantles the various forms of Shirk (associating partners with Allah) that had crept into popular practice. Shah Ismail Shaheed begins by establishing the fundamental principle that all forms of worship, supplication, reliance, and veneration must be directed exclusively to Allah alone. He then meticulously categorizes the different types of Shirk prevalent in society, including seeking help from the dead, making vows at graves, wearing amulets for protection, and attributing knowledge of the unseen to anyone other than Allah. Each practice is examined in light of Quranic verses and authentic Ahadith, making the arguments both academically rigorous and spiritually compelling. The author does not merely condemn these practices but explains the underlying theological errors that lead people toward them, helping readers develop a critical understanding of why certain beliefs and actions violate the principles of pure monotheism.

This English edition published by Darussalam maintains the clarity and directness that made the original Urdu text so effective. The translation preserves the authoritative tone of Shah Ismail Shaheed while ensuring that English-speaking readers can fully grasp the concepts being presented. Footnotes and references have been added to provide additional context for readers who may be unfamiliar with the historical and cultural background of the issues discussed. Taqwiyat-ul-Iman is particularly valuable for new Muslims seeking to build a solid foundation in their faith, for students of Islamic studies who want to understand the historical development of Aqeedah in the subcontinent, and for anyone who wishes to examine their own beliefs and practices against the benchmark of authentic Islamic teachings. The book serves as both a corrective text for those who may have grown up with diluted or compromised beliefs and as a reference guide for those involved in Dawah work. Its message remains as relevant today as it was when it was first written, reminding Muslims that the strength of their faith lies in the purity and sincerity of their belief in Allah alone.`,
